docs.abstract: Martin Shkreli, convicted of fraud for actions around his hedge fund, is going to prison. So far, Elizabeth Holmes, who sold falsehoods about her blood-testing business, is not.
docs.snippet: Martin Shkreli, convicted of fraud for actions around his hedge fund, is going to prison. So far, Elizabeth Holmes, who sold falsehoods about her blood-testing business, is not.
docs.lead_paragraph: Few white-collar defendants have been more reviled than the man known as the Pharma Bro, Martin Shkreli, even before he was convicted on multiple counts of securities fraud. The Atlantic called him “the perfect and very hateable combination of arrogance, youth, and avarice,” after he gained notoriety for acquiring the rights to generic drugs for rare diseases and then jacking up the prices.

headline.main: Shkreli vs. Holmes: 2 Frauds, 2 Divergent Outcomes. Were They Fair?

docs.abstract: The United States government essentially declared Qualcomm a national champion, but a rise in anti-foreign sentiment may hurt the chip maker, too.
docs.snippet: The United States government essentially declared Qualcomm a national champion, but a rise in anti-foreign sentiment may hurt the chip maker, too.
docs.lead_paragraph: Qualcomm has slain a lion, but baited a dragon. Having the United States government essentially declare the firm a national champion allowed the chip maker to defend itself from rival Broadcom’s $117 billion takeover bid. But a rise in anti-foreign sentiment may hurt Qualcomm, too — since it’s still waiting for China to approve its own $44 billion acquisition of NXP Semiconductors.

headline.main: Qualcomm Could Find Itself in the Middle of Escalating Tensions With China

docs.abstract: With roughly 850 stations, iHeartRadio still wields considerable power in the industry. But it has been weighed down by a $20 billion debt load for years.
docs.snippet: With roughly 850 stations, iHeartRadio still wields considerable power in the industry. But it has been weighed down by a $20 billion debt load for years.
docs.lead_paragraph: Ed Sheeran, Eminem, Maroon 5 and Cardi B all performed on Sunday night as part of the iHeartRadio Music Awards, a testament to the company’s dominance over the radio business. Its roughly 850 stations, the most of any American broadcaster, still wield considerable hitmaking power, even in the age of streaming.

headline.main: IHeartMedia, U.S.’s Largest Radio Broadcaster, Files for Bankruptcy
headline.print_headline: Bankrupt, IHeartMedia Has Deals To Cut Debt

docs.abstract: John Legere says T-Mobile’s acquisition of Sprint will help America lead in wireless technology. His reasoning is compelling, provided Mr. Legere sticks to his word.
docs.snippet: John Legere says T-Mobile’s acquisition of Sprint will help America lead in wireless technology. His reasoning is compelling, provided Mr. Legere sticks to his word.
docs.lead_paragraph: John Legere, the chief executive of T-Mobile, believes in second chances. And he has a point. Mr. Legere said if regulators allow T-Mobile’s nearly $26.5 billion acquisition of Sprint — a deal they opposed in the past — it will help the United States lead in wireless technology. The rationale this time is compelling.

headline.main: T-Mobile’s 5G Argument to Regulators Is Compelling
